.TH BNDDIR 3RPGHSPEC  "June 2012" "ILE RPG Language Reference"
.SH NAME
BNDDIR
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
BNDDIR('binding-directory-name' {:'binding-directory-name'â¦})
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \fIBNDDIR\fR keyword specifies the list of binding directories that are used in symbol resolution\[char46]


A binding directory name can be qualified by a library name followed by a slash delimiter (\[char39]library-name/binding-directory-name\[char39])\[char46] The library name is the name of the library to be searched\[char46] If the library name is not specified, \fI*LIBL\fR is used to find the binding directory name\[char46] When creating a program using \fICRTBNDRPG\fR, the library list is searched at the time of the compile\[char46] When creating a module using \fICRTRPGMOD\fR, the library list is searched when the module is used to create a program or service program\[char46]


If \fIBNDDIR\fR is specified on both the control specification and on the command, all binding directories are used for symbol resolution\[char46] The \fIBNDDIR\fR on the control specification does not override the \fIBNDDIR\fR on the command\[char46]


If the \fIBNDDIR\fR keyword is not specified, then the value specified on the command is used\[char46]


You cannot use the \fIBNDDIR\fR, \fIACTGRP\fR, or \fISTGMDL\fR command parameters or keywords when creating a program with \fIDFTACTGRP\fR(\fI*YES\fR)\[char46]


See \fIDFTACTGRP\fR(\fI*YES\fR | \fI*NO\fR) for information on how the \fIBNDDIR\fR keyword affects the setting of the \fIDFTACTGRP\fR keyword\[char46]

